         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">OTTELIA OVALIFOLIA. ¶ As this Ottelia has now been raised in several European gardens from seeds procured by me, it may be interesting to give an illustration in the  ¶ Gardeners' Chronicle ¶ , copied...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">86.04.00e</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To the Gardeners' Chronicle</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: center; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from '<name key="Ottelia%20ovalifolia">Ottelia ovalifolia</name>', <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Gardeners' chronicle</seg>, 12 June 1886, p. 753 (B6.06.04). It is dated to late April 1886 as the latest date that it is likely to have been sent to have been published in that issue. </p>
               </note>OTTELIA OVALIFOLIA.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As this Ottelia has now been raised in several European gardens from seeds procured by me, it may be interesting to give an illustration in the </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Gardeners' Chronicle</seg>
               <seg style="">, copied from my </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Key to the System of Victorian Plants</seg>
               <seg style="">.</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B</seg>86.04.05, fig. 115(A).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> There should be no difficulty in naturalising this pretty aquatic in the South of Europe. The plant is also remarkable for its dimorphism, the flowers with preponderating stamens being the largest, those with preponderating styles and seeds being the smallest. <name key="Ottelia%20tenera">Ottelia tenera</name> is the plant in its first year's age. The dimorphism of the genus Ottelia seems never yet to have been illustrated. </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Ferd. von Mueller, Melbourne.</seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M's text is followed by a commentary on the genus, indicating that the 'species figured from a drawing made by Baron von Mueller, is an Australian plant, and few species are more worthy of cultivation in the aquarium'. The illustration differs very slightly from the woodcut in B86.04.05.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <name key="Ottelia%20ovalifolia">Ottelia ovalifolia</name>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <name key="Ottelia%20tenera">Ottelia tenera</name>
               </seg>
            </p>
